FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) — Health-care workers recounted the daily struggles of fighting the COVID-19 pandemic, and their personal moments with patients, at a memorial service led by Gov. Andy Beshear on Sunday to remember the more than 10,000 Kentuckians who died from the virus.Beshear noted that Kentucky’s death toll from the global pandemic has surpassed the population of many towns across the Bluegrass State.“Imagine any of those towns suddenly empty and you get an idea of the collective loss that this state has endured,” the governor said.Kentucky recently surpassed the grim milestone of 10,000 coronavirus-related deaths. Those lost in the pandemic were remembered in prayers and speeches during the ceremony at the state Capitol.Jamar Wattley, a nurse at Baptist Health La Grange, recalled praying with patients and seeing the “glow” in their faces while talking about loved ones. And sometimes he heard their final goodbyes.ADVERTISEMENT“I remember the feeling of sorrow because of the failure that I still feel that I was not able to get you over that hill onto the road to recovery,” he said.Jacqueline Woodward said she endured “the greatest tragedy” of her life when her husband, who led a critical-care nurse team, died of COVID-19 nearly a year ago.“Lord, I pray this pandemic will end soon,” she said.During the ceremony, Beshear announced that Kentucky-native Amanda Matthews has been commissioned to create a COVID-19 Memorial that will be placed on the statehouse grounds.___Follow more of AP’s pandemic coverage at https://apnews.com/hub/coronavirus-pandemic.